reviewText: This twisted thriller about a psychiatrist trying to save his patient from commiting suicide, while beginning to fade from reality, is somewhat confusing, but packed with flahses of intense scenes.Henry Letham (Ryan Gosling) threatens to commit suicide in three days, by shooting himself on the Brooklyn Bridge, at midnight that Saturday, as he turns twenty one. This act of suicide is identical to the one which his idol artist commited himself as he turned twenty one. His psychiatrist, or actually 'fill in' psychiatrist, Sam Foster (Ewan McGregor) takes the threat very seriously, due to the fact that he saved his current girlfriend (Naomi Watts) from the same experience.As the days draw nearer and still Sam feels as though he has nothing to go on, his own grip on 'reality' begins to slip away as he delves deeper and deeper into Henry's twisted past and strange illusions of the mind.The 'skips' that occur in this movie, which are mere movement which seem to 'fast forward' between Henry's past and future, seem to almost melt Sam and Henry together. Who can forget the scene where Sam is chasing Henry and grabs him and they switch off saying "I need some answers!"?Or the scene where they are both getting off two trains and Sam's face changes to Henry's? Overall, this movie is incredible.I give it four stars due to the fact that it requires some afterthoughts which take a long time to process, and we feel like we have lost some of the information we were gathering. it is hard in this movie to distinguish between reality and imagination, what is truth, what is a lie, what is there, and what isn't. But the acting is phenominal and the special effects rank in the top of what have passed my eyes."I'm losing my grip on reality."Great movie, great characters, good plot line, somewhat shaky, but enjoyable.

reviewText: My word, this is a bad movie.  Confusing, boring, senseless, pointless, shall I continue or are you beginning to get the point?  I am not sure what possesses an actor like Ewan McGregor to participate in a movie like this, but then again he has made tons of horrible movies (like the Pillow Book for example).  I am losing faith in Naomi Watts, who I once considered an ally in the neo-femme movement.  After this and her atrocious work in King Kong, I've nearly forgotten how good she was in Lynch's "Mulholland Drive".Speaking of D. Lynch, this movie is very much a rip-off of his style.  But it misses by a mile in it's attempts at surrealism.  Oh, and speaking again of neo-femmes falling from grace, who should turn up in a thankless cameo but none other than... Janeane Garafalo (I don't care if I misspelled her name after what she's done to us in the movement- i.e. become a turncoat).  How do you feminize Benedict Arnold?  Feel free to contact me with suggestions, but I think you catch my drift.No stars would be far more appropriate.

reviewText: "Stay" is a strange movie with a feeling of dark unreality about it.  Occupying an unusual place in the crossroads of horror, drama, metaphysical and thriller territory, the most basic description of its plot would be that it's about a psychiatrist (played by Ewan McGregor) trying to prevent one of his patients (Ryan Gosling) from committing suicide, and finding out along the way that the patient may possess some kind of supernatural attributes.  But it gets a lot weirder, more baffling even, as it goes along.  The initial glimpes of possible paranormal powers - like an unerring ability to make predictions about the future - and hints that Gosling may have committed some kind of crime in his past, give way to more difficult-to-quantify phenomena, as MacGregor finds the whole world around him turning into an unfamiliar place in which the rules of time and space no longer seem to apply.  If this is one you were thinking of getting but have heard one of the spoiler reviews that give away the ending, I'd urge you not to forego it for that reason.  For one thing, there's a lot of little things in the undercurrent - including right toward the end - that imply the 'resolutions' may not be as cut-and-dried as they seem at first glance.  Like 'Dark Water' and 'Mute Witness', this is one you really have to pay close attention to to catch all the little nuances.I just saw this one very recently so it's not like I'm going to rewatch it in the next week, but it's one I would like to see again in the next few months.  There are a lot of things that I think are going to be interesting to observe with hindsight, and I think that quite a few viewers may end up feeling the same way.
summary: Really Good And Enigmatic Metaphysical Mystery

reviewText: Lovers of "Stay" accuse its critics of "not understanding" the movie, or of being so dumb that we need to be spoon-fed a Hollywood narrative. So let me start by saying I understand it. I know the story it's telling - Henry Letham is dying on the road after an accident, and what we're seeing is a scenario constructed by his dying brain as he struggles with the decision to hang on or to give in to guilt and let go. This isn't fully revealed until the film's final minutes, but it is at that point made abundantly clear. So I get it. It's a very old story, at least as old as Ambrose Bierce's nineteenth-century short story "An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge". The story's fine. The problem I have with "Stay" is that as a film it's insufferably tedious.Twist movies only work when everything before the twist has been internally consistent - films like "The Usual Suspects", "Fight Club" and "The Sixth Sense" (or anything else by Shyamalan, to date) work so well because you're entirely drawn in by what you think is the story only to find out, in the final act, that you've been told a very different one. This requires respect for the art of storytelling, something Marc Forster and David Benihoff seem to have forgotten. Rather than crafting a strong narrative that can be radically reinterpreted through an unexpected final revelation - as Bierce did, and as Adrian Lyne and Bruce Joel Rubin did in what is essentially the same story, "Jacob's Ladder" - they seem to have decided that a concatenation of slightly unsettling scenes, nicely shot, snappily edited, and wrapped up with a cool soundtrack is an adequate substitute. It isn't. There's a fine line between confusion that intrigues (David Lynch) and confusion that bores (film school undergrads), and "Stay" spends way too much time on the wrong side of it. In the best twist movies, you never see it coming. Here, the indeterminability of everything demands it from the outset and you just can't wait for it to arrive. What's happening isn't frightening enough, nor compelling enough - though it is, again, in "Jacob's Ladder" - for you to remain very interested otherwise. It's like a mystery without clues. We're not even given a red herring to cling to; never offered a plausible explanation for what is happening until the very end.The fundamental problem seems to be that Ewan McGregor's Sam Foster is posited as the central character, so all your effort goes into figuring out what is happening to him, when Ryan Gosling's Henry Letham is actually the one you should be thinking about, the one whose story this is. Unless, of course, you read the dissolves and frequent line-crossing in the editing and the occasional reference to twins to indicate that Sam is another part of Henry, although why his dying brain should construct such an elaborate third-person scenario is never justified. As others have noted, the film goes to extraordinarily elaborate lengths trying to explore this convergence without making you feel for a moment that this is interesting or meaningful, let alone plausible. Ultimately, you just get the feeling you're being elaborately toyed with, so you simply disengage, enjoy the music and the images, and wait for the big reveal. When it comes, it isn't even that good - while it does carry some emotional weight, it's ultimately as unmotivated as what's come before it. At least Jacob Singer had a mission, a goal, something he had to do in order to break free. All Henry seems to have is a brain haemorrhage.Knowing how it ends, I suspect that if you watched this film a few more times you might discover the arcane semiotic system that Forster has presumably deployed here which points to the truth of what's happening, right from the start, e.g. Forster has stated in interviews that McGregor's trousers are stupidly short because that's how Henry would see them from his prone position on the road. Great, but who the hell is going to work that out while watching the film? Nobody, which is why Forster's been forced to explain it in interviews. I really hope such detailed symbolism is there. Films like this should bear repeated viewings. But the real test is whether they work the first time you see them. This one doesn't.
summary: A mystery without clues, a twist without a plot (includes spoilers)

That being said the film doesn't ultimately make any sense, atleast in my mind. If that doesn't bother you, then that is fine. The acting is good, there are some intense scenes, some people may be dead, or in a dreamlike state but I couldn't honestly tell you to save my life. What I do know is that I truly love movies..and I have never left a movie feeling so ultimately unsatisfied as I did after "Stay".

reviewText: Visually, this movie was amazing.  There were so many visual trickeries in this movie that my eyes were glued to the screen, hoping not to miss any cool details.  "Stay" heavily deals with the question, "what is real?" and if you pay attention to what's going on in the background, you'll be asking "is this real?" too.  In fact, I heard one guy in the theater blurt out, "what the *bleep* is going on??" in one scene.What I really enjoyed was the fact that the visuals, despite all the cool trickeries, did not seem overwhelming or over the top.  In fact, it came just short of being over the top.  In less capable hands, all the cool camera angles, fades and transitions, filter effects, and interior set pieces would have ended up being overblown and cheesy.  The director Marc Foster and all the people behind cinematography, CG effects, and production design deserve a major standing ovation for their efforts.I'm being more subjective here, but I absolutely loved the music too.  Fittingly atmospheric and trippy, the music adeptly underscored the visuals, and I'll be sure to get the soundtrack CD.However, I have to say that I took objection to the movie's use of the song "Angel" by Massive Attack.  Now, I love Massive Attack, and I really like the song "Angel."  It's just that I've already heard that same song used in dreamy/trippy scenes in several other movies.  Massive Attack's vibe fits the movie perfectly well, so I don't mind their choice in the band.  But why couldn't they use one of Massive Attack's lesser known but just as atmospheric and trippy songs instead?  Hearing that song in "Stay" made me go, "oh no, not again," and took me out of the film.All in all, "Stay" was a huge treat for my eyes and ears.Beyond all the production gloss, however, I have to confess that I walked away from the theater feeling a bit underwhelmed.  There just wasn't enough substance to tie it all together.  A lot of the visual cool stuff ended up being just that: cool stuff, and nothing more.  It's like receiving a big gift box, spending time rattling it to guess what's inside, only to unwrap it and discover that it's just one piece of Godiva chocolate in a big fluffy packaging.  Still delicious, and you'd rather have it than not, but at the same time, it's disappointing, and the joy is too fleeting.  Without all the visual fluff, the story of "Stay" probably could have been told in one 45-minute "Outer Limits" or "Twilight Zone" episode.Acting-wise, I thought Ryan Gosling hit the perfect note for his role.  Naomi Watts gave a decent, if not particularly memorable, performance.  Ewan McGregor's performance, however, was a bit of a mixed bag.  There were moments where I thought he nailed it perfectly, and then there were moments where I thought he simply fell flat.  I like Ewan, but he more often than not seems to have at least one such moment in all his films, and that's such a shame.Speaking of which, I have to say that Bob Hoskins was amazing.  He was amazing in "Unleashed," and he was amazing in "Stay."  And sadly, his performance will probably go unnoticed by many.Overall, I enjoyed this movie.  I'm a sucker for "what is real?"-type storylines, and if "Stay" had more substance to it, I probably would have given it a 4.5-star rating.  As it is, the movie deserves about 3 or 3.5 stars.  But I really, really loved the visual flair of this film, and I dug the atmosphere it created.  And since Amazon won't let me do ratings in 0.5 increments, I'm bumping it up to a 4-star rating.By the way, if you are interested in watching this film, then do go to a theater and watch it on a big screen.  I feel that "Stay"'s visual flair just won't be the same on a smaller TV screen.
summary: Substance was slightly lacking, but your eyes and ears will be in heaven.

reviewText: Wow! I'm always pleasantly surprised when I see that a few brave souls are still making films for intelligent adults. In recent years, the rare treats--for those of us who demand more from movies than we usually get--have included MULHOLLAND DRIVE, SWIMMING POOL, MEMENTO, THE JACKET, GOOD NIGHT AND GOOD LUCK, CAPOTE, BROKEBACK MOUNTAIN, A HISTORY OF VIOLENCE, and...STAY.This is a fascinating film, and one that demands close attention and multiple viewings. I watched it on the advice of friends whose opinions I trust, and I'm glad I did. Watch closely, and you'll see a great deal. I won't spoil the payoff, but the title of this review is a crucial line of dialogue, spoken by Ewan McGregor near the end of the film. The whole world, indeed!I'm disappointed that STAY got such negative reviews and did so poorly at the box office, but I can't say I'm surprised. The new generations of American critics and film audiences have been conditioned to expect loud explosions and crude, adolescent humor as entertainment, and a film like this is obviously going to confuse and bore them. But for those of you out there who actually know who Hitchcock, Kurosawa, Antonioni, Fellini, Peter Greenaway and David Lynch are (not to mention Ambrose Bierce), you're in for a feast. There's more going on here than in most of the usual Hollywood "product." Stay with STAY--you won't regret it.
summary: "If this is a dream, the whole world is inside it."

reviewText: Many people quite understandably dismiss `Stay' as confusing, incoherent mess that pretends to be a supernatural or psychological thriller. On the other hand there are people who defend the film, saying that the disappointed audiences are actually misinformed about the content of the film, which should be promoted as something other than thriller.Which side is right after all? It is a tantalizing question, and you will never know it, but at least it is true that `Stay' shares elements commonly found in recent thrillers that benefit from the spooky, supernatural elements (whatever they are). If Ewan McGregor plays a psychiatrist in New York, and finds his new patient Henry (Ryan Gosling) can predict the change of the weather, it is definitely a thriller. Not only that; Henry declares he is going to die in three days; Henry insists that a blind chess player (Bob Hoskins) is actually his father. So who is Henry, or where are we now?Frankly, some of us do not care, and I am among them. The greatest problem of the film is, for all the intriguing and mesmerizing tricks of visuals and editing, the film gets boring soon. Now don't get me wrong here before you dismiss my review, for I know some thrillers do not necessarily needs a single, definite answer. Thrillers can be open to multiple interpretations, and they can be still good thrillers. But `Stay' is not one of them, throwing in clues, visual or verbal, all of which just create confusion, the simplest confusion that refuses to stimulate our brains.Many people say that 'Stay's is confusing, but here is the real reason for our complaint about the confusion in `Stay.' - it is boring. Now take a look at another kind of confusion, which is also mind-boggling but more intriguing than this one. Yes, another Naomi Watts `thriller' `Mullholand Dr.' which is more challenging, audacious, even ridiculous, but still more fascinating than `Stay.' I know it is not fair to compare Mark Forster with David Lynch, for no one can think like the latter, but at least the nightmarish feeling of `Stay' could have been developed into something more other-worldly (like the Hollywood of Lynch's own vision). But Forster even does not explore that direction, stopping in the realm of pretty conventional supernatural thrillers.I am truly disappointed with the film because it is exceptionally well-acted. McGregor shows the depth of the character while Naomi Watts, despite her underwritten role, brings certain amount of warmth and humanity into the film's world, which should be less about the rather flashy camera and more about Henry and his world itself.
summary: For All its Striking Visual Flair, Not Intriguing as 'Thriller' and Not Fascinating as Something Else

reviewText: Stay is the story of Sam Foster, a psychiatrist played by Ewan McGregor, who is introduced to a suicidal patient by the name of Henry Letham (played by Ryan Gosling). As Sam and Henry get to know one another, the line between what is real and what isn't becomes blurred. By the end of the film, the viewer feels as Sam and Henry do; confused, cloudy and like they are living in a dream.Stay is one of the most visually stunning, dreamlike, hypnotic, and brilliant pieces of film you will ever have the pleasure of viewing. The story moves along with such grace and surreality that the viewer begins to feel a part of the film. Every aspect of the movie is crafted with perfection. There is not a second of film or note of music that does not, in some way, stimulate the mind and enhance the story. The attention to detail in Stay is shocking compared to what generally passes as movie making.Ewan McGregor and Ryan Gosling deliver acting brilliance, and are joined by the exceptional performances of Naomi Watts and Bob Hoskins. There isn't a misplaced line, or unbelievable moment in the film.Where Stay excels is at creating an intense experience; an immersion in the story that lacks in most modern films. I felt completely lost to myself while watching the movie. Few films deliver such immersion.Some will say that the film is "complicated" or "artsy." There are many pretentious films that exist to call attention to the director/writer/producer, etc. Stay is not one of them. Every second of film in Stay is crafted to enhance the story, and enhance the story it does.This is not a film for everyone, and I can see where some may not like it. Stay is non-linear, like great poetry, music, art and life. It does not go where you want it to go, or where so many films have conditioned our mind that it should go. Stay stays on its own course, and in doing so treats you to a haunting movie experience that you will not soon forgot, and a movie you will watch over and over again.Total Score (out of 100) = 10050 (out of 50).
